he 'vegan turn' in literary theoretical analysis via essays that explore literature from across a range of historical periods, cultures and textual forms. It provides thematic explorations (such as veganism and race and veganism and gender) and covers a wide range of genres (from the philosophical essay to speculative fiction, and from poetry to the graphic novel, to name a few). The volume also provides an extensive annotated bibliography summarising existing work within the emergent field of vegan studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aEthics in literature. 0aFood habits in literature. 0aVeganism in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Carol J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorkfelt, Sune, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulleid, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Stewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Amy-Leigh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsfahani-Hammond, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIyer, Sangamithra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemmerer, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanger, Armin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedoro, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilburn, Josh, econtributor.4ctb